{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611768"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:15:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16243"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16243"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.05,0.19,0.08,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8934"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115389"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8934"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16243"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97392"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"563"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"6827"},{"type":"tags","id":"6829"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8651"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21264"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115389"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anatomical configuration of the thorax and upper abdomen undergoes significant changes during development from the neonatal period to adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes anatomical differences between neonatal and adult thoracic configuration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The neonatal thorax has a rounder cross-section compared to the adult thorax","The neonatal thorax has a more flattened appearance than the adult thorax","The neonatal diaphragm is more dome-shaped than the adult diaphragm","The neonatal ribs are more obliquely positioned than adult ribs","The neonatal thoracic cavity has a larger volume relative to body size"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eneonatal thorax has a rounder cross-section\u003C/strong\u003E compared to the adult thorax, which becomes more oval or flattened in the anterior-posterior dimension with age. This anatomical difference affects respiratory mechanics and the positioning of thoracic and upper abdominal organs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eneonatal thorax has a more flattened appearance\u003C/strong\u003E is the opposite of the correct answer, as the neonatal thorax is actually rounder. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eneonatal diaphragm is more dome-shaped\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect since the neonatal diaphragm is actually flatter and more horizontal than in adults. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eneonatal ribs are more obliquely positioned\u003C/strong\u003E describes the opposite configuration, as neonatal ribs are actually more horizontal compared to adult ribs. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eneonatal thoracic cavity has a larger volume\u003C/strong\u003E relative to body size is incorrect because the neonatal thoracic cavity is proportionally smaller relative to body size. These anatomical differences have important implications for respiratory mechanics and the positioning of abdominal organs in neonates compared to adults.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The neonatal thorax is round in cross-section compared to the adult\u0027s more oval or flattened appearance.","The neonatal diaphragm is flatter and positioned more horizontally than in adults.","These anatomical differences affect respiratory mechanics and gastrointestinal positioning in neonates."],"references":["Dosman CF, Andrews D, Goulden KJ. Evidence-based milestone ages as a framework for developmental surveillance. Paediatr Child Health. 2012 Dec;17(10):561-8. doi: 10.1093/pch/17.10.561. PMID: 24294064; PMCID: PMC3549694","Sheldrick RC, Schlichting LE, Berger B, Clyne A, Ni P, Perrin EC, Vivier PM. Establishing New Norms for Developmental Milestones. Pediatrics. 2019 Dec;144(6):e20190374. doi: 10.1542/peds.2019-0374. Epub 2019 Nov 14. PMID: 31727860; PMCID: PMC6889967","Lissauer, T., \u0026 Carroll, W. (Eds.). (2021). Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book: Illustrated Textbook of Paediatrics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Indrio F, Neu J, Pettoello-Mantovani M, Marchese F, Martini S, Salatto A, Aceti A. Development of the Gastrointestinal Tract in Newborns as a Challenge for an Appropriate Nutrition: A Narrative Review. Nutrients. 2022 Mar 28;14(7):1405. doi: 10.3390/nu14071405. PMID: 35406018; PMCID: PMC9002905."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97392"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16243"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97392"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:31:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:34:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8934"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115389"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"